        "description": "The Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law exponents (alpha, beta) must be selected from peer-reviewed calibration studies; sensitivity of GHI to ±1-sigma variation in each exponent must be documented; 95th-percentile Monte Carlo GHI must remain below clinical threshold."
      },
      "rationale": "The Giersiepen-Wurzinger hemolysis model is used with exponents alpha=0.785 and beta=2.416 from the primary calibration literature. LOW CONFIDENCE FLAG: Published calibration datasets yield a 1-sigma uncertainty of ±0.12 on alpha and ±0.31 on beta, producing a wide GHI uncertainty band (CV=34% at the highest-shear operating point). This limitation is documented explicitly. Monte Carlo sampling (N=5000) over the joint exponent distribution confirms that the 95th-percentile GHI remains 18% below the clinical threshold of 0.8 g/dL. The conservative UQ envelope is the primary basis for accepting this factor at Gradation 3 despite the wide parametric uncertainty; the honest documentation of the confidence limitation is reflected in the decision rationale."
